EAID_E5E010C2_C1F3_4986_AA9A_C71C1926360.definitie: The details of the residence and address of the REGISTERED NATURAL PERSON
EAID_E5E010C2_C1F3_4986_AA9A_C71C1926360.toelichting:
<memo>#Notes#It is a data group type that consists of the following (group) attribute types:
 Occupational origin
 Location Description
 and the following relationships:
 is registered on number designation
 Stays at berth
 Stays at the location.
 Stays in a residence object
 Stays on location in hometown
 The data group type is derived from the address group (A.1.13) in the BRP (version 1.0, October 2014). This involves a residence address of a person each time a residential or letter address. With the Data Group Type of residence address, we model the BRP only residential addresses for the BRP. We model BRP-Storing places as a correspondence address at Subject as a correspondence address. If only a letter address is included in the BRP with a person, another source may still have a home address. That is why the address origin indicates whether or not the residence address has the BRP as an authentic source. See also the explanation of the latter attribute species.

EAID_52A545A9_393C_46fd_9B18_E2D4F14BAE5.name: Retaining wall
EAID_52A545A9_393C_46fd_9B18_E2D4F14BAE5.definitie: A retaining wall or retaining wall is a rigid, earth- or water-retaining structure that can achieve high stability due to a large weight and a wide base. A retaining wall is usually made of reinforced concrete, but other materials can also be used.

EAID_82B46E2A_F5D4_46d6_AAF4_DD9332256CD.name: Vault
EAID_82B46E2A_F5D4_46d6_AAF4_DD9332256CD.definitie:
An overhang is a civil engineering structure with which a road (crosswise) vaults another road, a square or a watercourse. In the case of a waterway, shipping is (often) not possible under the structure, but the water surface is still free. A vault can be compared to a bridge, 
However, in this case, the bridge often does not consist of a road surface but of a building. 
In other words, it is usually not part of a road

EAID_98FF24AC_77FF_4ff4_A270_FED239EE172.name: diver
EAID_98FF24AC_77FF_4ff4_A270_FED239EE172.definitie: Artwork for water management, consisting of a tube-shaped construction installed under a road or railway or in a dam.

EAID_04197202_7CEC_4168_90AF_9E0E8194653.name: Wildlife Facility
EAID_04197202_7CEC_4168_90AF_9E0E8194653.definitie: Facility near a road or railway, other than an ecoduct, in order to prevent or limit as far as possible the negative effects on the fauna resulting from that work.

EAID_081F6CAD_9067_4e15_932C_D1EC56ECF41.name: Fish passage
EAID_081F6CAD_9067_4e15_932C_D1EC56ECF41.definitie: An artificial passage for the benefit of fish migration near works of art in waters.

EAID_D6267A4B_A0E6_4701_AFC5_A8FB65242EB.name: Bottom Trap
EAID_D6267A4B_A0E6_4701_AFC5_A8FB65242EB.definitie: Jump into the bottom of a watercourse.

EAID_10BF87AA_435A_44f3_B59B_BF714F41A8B.definitie: Metal mast or scaffold to support conductor wires for the transmission of high-voltage electricity.

EAID_97052753_B91D_4724_9156_C01384256C0.definitie: An artificial, movable flood barrier that can close or open the connection between two bodies of water and is equipped with doors or gates for this purpose.

EAID_EB48C4AE_664C_4a4f_B5B0_84B37AB42E6.name: breakwater

EAID_F33674C4_3F2D_4023_9B8D_93145BA555E.definitie: Fixed (non-floating) hydraulic structure for the mooring of ships and intended to load and unload these ships from the shore.

EAID_80429AC4_D914_4181_B525_AE9C4BD6EB1.name: weir
EAID_80429AC4_D914_4181_B525_AE9C4BD6EB1.definitie: A structure with a fixed threshold or a movable valve, which serves to regulate the water level upstream and downstream.

EAID_0CB485FB_9420_4c3b_8BFA_3917D896594.definitie: Container or basket in public spaces with a permanent character; intended for the collection of (usually loose) waste.

Departures.

(dimming) when the situation allows.

downstream from floating debris and the like.

Construction intended to reduce glare to road users by backlighting. 
prevent.

Silted up outside the dikes, unvegetated soil that is exposed to almost every high tide 
flooded.

EAID_A3D89DBF_39FC_42ca_9807_E3A1F7675E9.name: path
EAID_A3D89DBF_39FC_42ca_9807_E3A1F7675E9.definitie: Paved area for road traffic and air traffic on land. This includes runways for air traffic.

EAID_C375F6A0_6F1F_40f7_8775_7168D686BAB.name: water
EAID_C375F6A0_6F1F_40f7_8775_7168D686BAB.definitie:
Ground surface basically covered with water.
 Examples are: river, canal, stream, sea, lake, surface water in general. Objects that are periodically covered with water as part of water management are also included.

EAID_8AB25ACF_6D63_4a7e_824A_C7850018A0F.name: railway
EAID_8AB25ACF_6D63_4a7e_824A_C7850018A0F.definitie:
Paved area for rail traffic.
Examples are: railway, metro track, tram track

EAID_3CE9E3CE_AF74_4af0_8D5D_9E213C5533E.name: terrain
EAID_3CE9E3CE_AF74_4af0_8D5D_9E213C5533E.definitie:
Characterized by a physical appearance, visibly bounded piece of land. 
Terrain is used to indicate a visibly (tangibly) bounded piece of land for which a certain physical appearance is typical. Examples are: forest, landscape, buildings, agricultural area. It is important that the plot of land has a visible boundary with adjacent geo-objects.

EAID_A3FDA813_30B9_4057_893A_9A5EC23A7F2.name: work of art
EAID_A3FDA813_30B9_4057_893A_9A5EC23A7F2.definitie:
Civil-engineering work for the infrastructure of roads, waterways, railways, flood defences and/or pipelines and not intended for permanent human residence.
This includes bridging, water management works and flood defence structures. Bridging can be: bridge, viaduct, aqueduct etc. An example of a water management project is a lock.    
Examples of water-retaining structures are weirs and fixed dams.

EAID_4DAE2CCA_63AC_47a9_AD90_25E18C78072.name: Landscape area
EAID_4DAE2CCA_63AC_47a9_AD90_25E18C78072.definitie:
'Geographical area' means a delimited and named area described by a geographical unit. 
The boundaries are not always precisely defined (e.g. Polder, Central Netherlands, River Region, Veluwe, South Limburg, Coastal Area).

EAID_2F194CDF_84E2_440b_9075_01546D2E7D5.name: Functional area
EAID_2F194CDF_84E2_440b_9075_01546D2E7D5.definitie: Bounded and named area described by a functional unit (e.g. business park, bungalow park, public park, cemetery, marina, wind farm, recreation area.

EAID_E82A3EF5_205B_44b4_878E_D6CA300C3D3.name: Administrative area
EAID_E82A3EF5_205B_44b4_878E_D6CA300C3D3.definitie: Area demarcated on the basis of laws or regulations that serves as a unit of political/administrative responsibility or for business operations

EAID_23F16A5E_0812_4c18_BEBE_1F9D54F2472.name: deck
EAID_23F16A5E_0812_4c18_BEBE_1F9D54F2472.definitie: Part of the superstructure of the bridge directly loaded by traffic.

EAID_1AB55365_EE1D_4579_9146_332D2CE9336.name: abutment
EAID_1AB55365_EE1D_4579_9146_332D2CE9336.definitie: On-site support structure of a transition from the earth track to a work of art.

EAID_49B6E319_EDEC_452d_B726_1342DDFDC0F.name: pillar
EAID_49B6E319_EDEC_452d_B726_1342DDFDC0F.definitie: Support structure of bridges and similar structures.

EAID_1ED7C8AF_655D_45a4_87BC_C63E00ACF79.name: Sloof
EAID_1ED7C8AF_655D_45a4_87BC_C63E00ACF79.definitie: Part of the face for the transfer of forces to the subsoil or the foundation.

EAID_309ECF0B_EEF8_44f2_83E8_DCD6AF1E271.name: Pylon
EAID_309ECF0B_EEF8_44f2_83E8_DCD6AF1E271.definitie: Above the superstructure protruding support structure for cables (cables)

EAID_62CF8BF1_433B_41be_9847_E76C9BF8D47.name: basin
EAID_62CF8BF1_433B_41be_9847_E76C9BF8D47.definitie: Water trough, such as a swimming pool or a dock.

EAID_165F5A87_BFAF_48d4_BF5E_EB24AFAD283.name: Settling tank
EAID_165F5A87_BFAF_48d4_BF5E_EB24AFAD283.definitie: A closed reservoir in which the wastewater is temporarily collected with a sludge cleaning facility.

EAID_8F89D523_F5EA_4d63_B146_85C90B64523.name: Location transformer
EAID_8F89D523_F5EA_4d63_B146_85C90B64523.definitie: Building in which transformer(s) are placed for electricity supply.

EAID_A844B5D1_97E4_44f7_AF87_1FC70CC685D.name: Wind turbine
EAID_A844B5D1_97E4_44f7_AF87_1FC70CC685D.definitie: Turbine in which wind pressure is converted into mechanical energy.

EAID_92E24D9C_66BB_481b_9EC3_30326D472EE.name: Open shed
EAID_92E24D9C_66BB_481b_9EC3_30326D472EE.definitie:
Lightweight building with an open façade that cannot be moved, intended as a storage or 
workshop or as temporary accommodation for other purposes.

EAID_2DC17561_B169_431b_A056_E0B77FD9906.name: storage tank
EAID_2DC17561_B169_431b_A056_E0B77FD9906.definitie: Storage facility for liquids. Only above-ground storage tanks are included.

EAID_879585CD_9E23_4c23_BB1F_608FFE2DBE5.name: roof
EAID_879585CD_9E23_4c23_BB1F_608FFE2DBE5.definitie: A separate enclosure resting on columns.

EAID_79F8E409_DB3B_4ac8_A26C_BF98879DDE9.name: bunker
EAID_79F8E409_DB3B_4ac8_A26C_BF98879DDE9.definitie: A bunker is a military defensive structure that provides a certain amount of protection against shelling and bombing.

EAID_A3690E53_6DFB_4653_8DBB_271C407E50A.name: Feed silo
EAID_A3690E53_6DFB_4653_8DBB_271C407E50A.definitie: Livestock feed storage facility, consisting of a vertical container with an opening at the bottom.

EAID_FC0154D4_D530_45ec_9118_47FE60102A8.name: barn
EAID_FC0154D4_D530_45ec_9118_47FE60102A8.definitie: A free-standing, prefabricated or not, non-permit-required structure that is used to store goods and can also serve as a workspace.

EAID_72E02650_7BBA_44fb_92FE_EA0D96C317F.name: wire grid
EAID_72E02650_7BBA_44fb_92FE_EA0D96C317F.definitie: Artificial terrain fencing, other than a fauna fence, in the form of predominantly wooden, metal or plastic upright poles with one or more wires in between.

EAID_7F97CEF2_6DD5_4b5d_B2CC_5E8DC1A4BF5.name: Fauna Grid
EAID_7F97CEF2_6DD5_4b5d_B2CC_5E8DC1A4BF5.definitie: Artificially applied separation of metal wire between poles, intended for guiding animals.

EAID_734C7CA8_048A_45d6_9D36_5E1C11926DE.name: boom
EAID_734C7CA8_048A_45d6_9D36_5E1C11926DE.definitie:
A striking tree that is not part of another tree or tree 
shrub planting.

EAID_E2160D19_3EF4_4d1f_AA72_ABDC9DB655B.name: haag
EAID_E2160D19_3EF4_4d1f_AA72_ABDC9DB655B.definitie: A row-shaped partition of very limited width consisting of planted contiguous shrubs.

EAID_93C33FCD_CE3E_4626_BE1C_2C04DFBE92A.name: watercourse
EAID_93C33FCD_CE3E_4626_BE1C_2C04DFBE92A.definitie: A channel intended for water management that usually contains permanent water (such as river, canal, stream, ditch, moat).

EAID_04C2F9CD_C085_42ea_B809_A220EC77E93.name: Expanse of water
EAID_04C2F9CD_C085_42ea_B809_A220EC77E93.definitie: All surfaces that are fairly permanently covered with fresh water. (such as lake, puddle, fen, pond).

EAID_7BAB1E20_37BE_424d_8DF4_3CC774A80A5.name: ditch, dry ditch
EAID_7BAB1E20_37BE_424d_8DF4_3CC774A80A5.definitie: A trench dug for the purpose of water management, which may or may not be covered with water.

EAID_378815D0_1E69_452e_BFB2_12057B87DDD.name: river
EAID_378815D0_1E69_452e_BFB2_12057B87DDD.definitie:
The water, which is used for atmospheric precipitation on sloping terrains, 
flows, insofar as it does not evaporate or be disposed of by plants. 
together into a watercourse and flows to 
low-lying areas. Such a natural run-off is called a 
river.

EAID_E66A181B_6E63_41ab_8504_48011E8EB16.name: ditch
EAID_E66A181B_6E63_41ab_8504_48011E8EB16.definitie:
General name for a watercourse of limited width 
containing stagnant or only slow-moving water.

EAID_49C323E6_EB11_4970_80DB_5421EDF5A71.name: channel
EAID_49C323E6_EB11_4970_80DB_5421EDF5A71.definitie:
A large watercourse that has been dug and is used for shipping and/or 
water transport.

EAID_7D70E2B4_D37F_477f_B86F_6482642999D.name: stream
EAID_7D70E2B4_D37F_477f_B86F_6482642999D.definitie: A natural narrow watercourse without tides.

EAID_20B88C50_0BA4_4f08_B2BE_13390224353.name: canal
EAID_20B88C50_0BA4_4f08_B2BE_13390224353.definitie:
A moat is a ditch dug with water, which is mainly 
occurs in ancient cities.

EAID_904A34AE_A441_4e7e_A708_5BFE73338C5.name: source
EAID_904A34AE_A441_4e7e_A708_5BFE73338C5.definitie:
Groundwater that has been extracted naturally from the earth's surface 
appears.

EAID_66AD6874_2EE5_46b2_9DFA_C0836221D74.name: haven
EAID_66AD6874_2EE5_46b2_9DFA_C0836221D74.definitie:
A suitable berth for ships, natural or dug 
water basin by the sea or on the banks of a river or inland waterway, which provides shelter from wind and waves.

EAID_C0610D39_3724_48b0_9EC7_966D5F63634.name: lake, puddle, fen, pond
EAID_C0610D39_3724_48b0_9EC7_966D5F63634.definitie: A mass of stagnant land surface water.

EAID_5A24808B_6B68_44ee_A920_9E1DF704CCD.definitie: The reference model is made up of object types, attribute types (data from the object types) and relationships (relationships between the object types). We portray an object type with a rectangle, separated in two parts by a horizontal lines of the object type is mentioned in the upper part of rectangle, the lower part is scrutinated for the attribute species. For the sake of readability, the attribute species in diagrams in the catalog are not shown. Object types that are part of any (catalog of a) basic registration is the rectangle an orange plane (object type A in the example). King has added the other object types. A white rectangle visualizes an object type that has been compiled from several other object types. This is a so -called generalization of object types. The latter object types are in turn specializations of the generalized object type and point with an arrow with a closed arrow point to the generalized object type. A generalized object type has a "fat" framework (object type C) as one or more of the specializations thereof are part of any (catalog of a) basic registration. In a blue plane are the object types that are not generalizations of other object types and are not part of any (catalog of a) basic registration (objecttye B). There are relationships between the object types, the display of connected agencies of object types. The relationships are unidirectional (from source to goal) with the mention of cardinality (the possible quantities of object types connected to the source and purpose). in the diagram has an object of the object A type of relationship With zero, one or more objects (0, *) of the object B. Type B. Conversely, it can be deduced from the diagram that an object B is related to exactly one object (1) of object type A. An object of the object type D has a relationship with one or more (1,*) objects of the object B. An object of type B is related to zero, one or more (0,*) objects of the object D. A relationship (name1) that is part of any (catalog of a) basic registration is "fatter" than relationships (name2) for which this does not apply: the relationships that King has added. An object of type E that has a relationship with an object of type F or has a relationship with an object of the type G is in the diagram. A Works Council Contraint indicated
